Laravel [API Resources](https://laravel.com/docs/6.x/eloquent-resources) are intended as a layer between Eloquent and the JSON response. So they follow the &quot;rules&quot; of the Model / Collection classes since the final scope is to have a JSON representation &quot;out of the box&quot; of these two classes.

In order to achieve your goal you should not use the API Resources, but you can always create a &quot;default&quot; way for all your collections. In my opinion the best way is creating a trait so you can reuse it in each controller you need. Something like this:

```php
trait CustomJsonResponse
{
  
  function toJsonResponse($collection)
  {
    $data = [];

    foreach($collection as $model) {
      $data[$model-&gt;id] = $model-&gt;toArray
    }

    return response()-&gt;json([
      &#39;data&#39; =&gt; $model
      &#39;links&#39; =&gt; [...],
      &#39;meta&#39; =&gt; [...]
    ])
  }
}
```  

For the links and the meta part, just have a look at the [`PaginatedResourceResponse` source code](https://github.com/laravel/framework/blob/6.x/src/Illuminate/Http/Resources/Json/PaginatedResourceResponse.php) so you can reuse the part of code required to reproduce the same result.

You can format the JSON however you want by building it out as an array in PHP and `json_encode()`ing it for the return (which Laravel does for you if you return only the data).  Something like this (caveat: untested, coding while in the browser):
```php
$results = Model::all();

$data = [];

foreach($results as $entry)
{
    $data[strval($entry-&gt;id)] = [
        &#39;id&#39; =&gt; $entry-&gt;id,
        &#39;title&#39; =&gt; $entry-&gt;title,
        &#39;other&#39; =&gt; $entry-&gt;other
    ];
}

return $data;   // or explicitly: return json_encode($data);
```

